<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-01-28T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-01-28T02:00:00-05:00" n="113" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d113">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.002/1–2849: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-01-28T15:00:00+08:00">January
                                    28, 1949—3 p. m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received January 29—6:33 a. m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>260. Premier<note n="84" xml:id="d113fn84">Sun Fo.</note> and Foreign
                            Minister have already left Nanking probably en route Canton. Despite
                            statement by Vice Foreign <pb facs="0105" n="95" xml:id="pg_95"/>
                            Minister that they have gone to Shanghai for special purpose and are
                            returning Nanking, their houses are both entirely closed and empty.</p>
                        <p>Repeated Shanghai 116, Canton 13.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>